Q1Feedback: Two new σ-bonds and a new ring were formed at the expense of 1 π-bond in this reaction. This is a [4+2] cycloaddition, a Diels-Alder reaction specifically.
Q2Feedback: A [4+2] cycloaddition goes through a preferred endo TS. Note that this may not necessarily apply to all types of cycloaddition.
Q3Feedback: Both A and C are endo transition states with secondary orbital interaction between the two middle carbons of the diene and the carbonyl groups (all marked with *'s).
Q4Feedback: A point-of-view as shown will result in the hydrogens in question pointing toward the viewer. Thus both A and D (identical structures) are correct.

Q1Feedback: This reaction resulted in the migration of 1 σ-bond and a net change of zero σ or π-bond. The two flip-flop fragments contain 3 heavy atoms each. So this is a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement. A Claisen rearrangement, specifically.
Q2Feedback: The selectivity of a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement is determined by a 6-membered ring chair TS. Note that this may not necessarily apply to all types of sigmatropic rearrangement.
Q3Feedback: Only B is a chair TS. A is a boat TS, which will only happen when it is impossible to achieve the chair TS.
Q4Feedback: The TS suggest the two Me groups should be trans to each other. This is due to the original trans geometry of both double bonds, which must be maintained in the TS. This specific TS will give C. Its mirror image will give D.

Q1Feedback: A ring opening reaction wherein a σ-bond disappeared and a new π-bond is formed. This is an electrocyclic reaction. It is a little difficult to see because of the three-membered ring, but that's precisely the driving force of the reaction.
Q2Feedback: A 6 π-electrons thermal electrocyclic reaction, so it's disrotatory.

Q1Feedback: Two new σ-bonds and a new ring was formed from two fragments at the expense of 1 π-bond. This is a [4+2] cycloaddition. The dienophile is also very conveniently electron poor.
Q2Feedback: Diels-Alder reaction always prefer an endo TS which maximises the secondary orbital interactions.
Q3Feedback: (a) and (b) are exo TS's. (d) shows reaction at the wrong double bond. So the correct answer is (c).
Q4Feedback: The POV shown above will have all the three H's in question pointing toward the viewer.

Q1Feedback: This reaction resulted in the migration of 1 σ-bond and a net change of zero σ or π-bond. The two flip-flop fragments contain 3 heavy atoms each. So this is a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement. A Claisen rearrangement, specifically.
Q2Feedback: Claisen rearrangement follows a chair TS unless it is physically impossible.
Q3Feedback: (c) and (d) are the only chair TS's. (c) shows the unreacted double bond as trans instead of cis. So (d) is the correct answer.
Q4Feedback: A point-of-view from the top will result in the stereochemistry showed in (a).

Q1Feedback: Two fragments joining to form a new ring with concurrent generation of two σ-bonds at the expense of 1 π-bond. This is an [3+2] cycloaddition.
Q2Feedback: The endo TS is normally mentioned when it comes to cycloaddition. However, this only applies to Diels-Alder reaction. In the [3+2] version, the triple bond is linear, so there is no endo or exo orientation.

Q1Feedback: A ring is formed at the expense of 1 π-bond, which is converted into a σ-bond. This reaction is an electrocyclic reaction.
Q2Feedback: For electrocyclic reaction, the correct method is to use a POV looking at the bond being formed and working out the correct rotation.
Q3Feedback: This is a 6 π-electrons reaction under photochemical reaction. So the correct rotation is conrotatory. (b) is the correct answer. (a) and (d) are chair TS's, and should not apply to this type of reaction.
Q4Feedback: The highlighted rotation suggests one should end up with the Me groups trans to each other. Clockwise and anti-clockwise rotations lead to product (a) and (c).

Q1Feedback: A new ring is formed at the expense of 1 π-bond, which is converted into 1 σ-bond. This is a 4 π-electrons electrocyclic reaction called Nazarov reaction.
Q2Feedback: As it is an electrocyclic reaction, the conrotatory/disrotatory rule applies. In particular, this is a 4 π-electrons system under thermal conditions, so it's conrotatory.

Q1Feedback: The reaction proceeds by swapping 1 σ-bond with another, followed by tautomerisation to the ketone. The two flip-flopping fragments each has three heavy atoms. This is a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement, specifically an oxy-Cope rearrangement.
Q2Feedback: As with all [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangements, a chair TS is used to workout the stereoselectivity unless it is physically impossible.
Q3Feedback: (b) has the wrong geometry on a double bond. (a) is the wrong compound (difficult to see). (c) is the only correct answer which has the right connectivity and stereochemistry.
Q4Feedback: There are two recognisable points from the TS: (i) the tBu and Me are on opposite sides of the ring, and (ii) the new double bond should be trans. A top-down view will give (b) as the correct answer.

Q1Feedback: Careful analysis should show the breaking of a N－N bond and formation of a new C－C bond, and the usual curly arrows in a circle. So it's a sigmatropic rearrangement, a [5,5]-sigmatropic rearrangement to be precise.
Q2Feedback: A chair TS is only applicable to [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangements. This is a [5,5]-sigmatropic rearrangement, so none of these TS models are suitable.

Q1Feedback: Two new σ-bonds and a new ring formed, this is a [4+2] cycloaddition. The diene is electron rich, the dienophile is electron poor as is the norm with this reaction.
Q2Feedback: A [4+2] cycloaddition should follow an endo TS to maximise the beneficial secondary orbital interactions.
Q3Feedback: Only (b) and (d) are endo TS's with secondary orbital interactions. (d) will result in the OMe and iPrCO group being meta to each other, which is wrong. Thus (b) is the correct answer.
Q4Feedback: (a) has the wrong connectivity. A point-of-view. As shown above will result in the correct stereochemistry shown in (d).

Q1Feedback: The reaction proceeds by swapping 1 σ-bond with another, followed by hydrolysis and tautomerisation. The two flip-flopping fragments each has three heavy atoms. This is a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement, specifically an Ireland-Claisen rearrangement (one oxygen, 5 carbons).
Q2Feedback: As with all [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangements, a chair TS is used to workout the stereoselectivity unless it is physically impossible.
Q3Feedback: The key issue here is the geometry of the double bonds in the TMS-enolate. The OTMS group should be trans to the Me. The other double bond should be trans. Both (a) and (c) satisfy these so (d) is the correct answer.
Q4Feedback: The TS suggested that both Me groups will be on the same side of the ring. A top-down view will give (d) as the correct answer. Enantiomer (a) is also formed in equal amount, but will come from TS (a) in the previous question.

Q1Feedback: Two fragments coming together to form 2 new σ-bonds and a ring. This is a cycloaddition. The number of heavy atoms on each fragment indicated that it is a [4+2] cycloaddition.
Q2Feedback: A [4+2] cycloaddition should be applicable to an endo TS which maximises secondary orbital interaction.
Q3Feedback: The chiral centre will force the diene to approach from under the ring, which leaves (a) and (b). (a) will allow the overlap of the ester group with the two middle carbons of the diene, i.e. endo TS.
Q4Feedback: The highlighted point-of-view will result in the Me, CO<sub>2</sub>Me and one of the H pointing toward the viewer, and the remaining H pointing away. Thus (c) is the correct answer.

Q1Feedback: The reaction proceeds by swapping 1 σ-bond with another, followed by hydrolysis and tautomerisation. The two flip-flopping fragments each has three heavy atoms. This is a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement, specifically an oxy-Cope rearrangement.
Q2Feedback: [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangements are governed by chair TS's, unless they are physically impossible.
Q3Feedback: The relative stereochemistry is key. The OH is on the same side as the largest substituent, which eliminates (c). (b) has the wrong stereochemistry on one double bond. (a) has the wrong conformer for the six-membered ring. So (d) is the correct answer.
Q4Feedback: The C=C next to Ph must be trans. The TS suggests that the new C=C bond should be Z. So (c)is the only correct answer.
